43 ammunition manufacturer or dealer for breach of contract or express warranty as to
44 weapons, firearms, or ammunition purchased by the political subdivision or local
45 government authority.
46 (c)(d)(1) A county or municipal corporation may regulate the transport, carrying, or
47 possession of firearms by employees of the local unit of government, or by unpaid
48 volunteers of such local unit of government, in the course of their employment or
49 volunteer functions with such local unit of government; provided, however, that the
50 sheriff or chief of police shall be solely responsible for regulating and determining the
51 possession, carrying, and transportation of firearms and other weapons by employees
52 under his or her respective supervision so long as such regulations comport with state and
53 federal law.
54 (2) The commanding officer of any law enforcement agency shall regulate and determine
55 the possession, carrying, and transportation of firearms and other weapons by employees
56 under his or her supervision so long as such regulations comport with state and federal
57 law.
58 (3) The district attorney, and the solicitor-general in counties where there is a state court,
59 shall regulate and determine the possession, carrying, and transportation of firearms and
60 other weapons by county employees under his or her supervision so long as such
61 regulations comport with state and federal law.
62 (d)(e) Nothing contained in this Code section shall prohibit municipalities or counties, by
63 ordinance or resolution, from requiring the ownership of guns by heads of households
64 within the political subdivision.
65 (e)(f) Nothing contained in this Code section shall prohibit municipalities or counties, by
66 ordinance or resolution, from reasonably limiting or prohibiting the discharge of firearms
67 within the boundaries of the municipal corporation or county.
- 3 -

